{"amendments":[{"body":"`src/contexts/milestone_record/model.rs:347-378` and `src/adapters/fs.rs:2280-2318` serialize completion details with a raw `\", \"`-delimited string, but the only protection against `project_id`/`run_id`/`plan_hash` containing that delimiter is `debug_assert!`. In release builds those checks disappear, and `ProjectId::new` / `RunId::new` still accept commas and spaces (`src/shared/domain.rs:804-838`). A legal id like `\"foo, bar\"` makes `CompletionJournalDetails::parse` fail, which means the repair path in `append_event_if_missing` (`src/adapters/fs.rs:2416-2493`) cannot merge or backfill replayed completion events. The result is duplicate completion journal rows instead of the intended idempotent repair whenever a replay adds missing `run_id`, `plan_hash`, or `outcome_detail`.","rationale":"The new lineage work explicitly relies on replay/backfill of completion metadata after partial failures; delimiter-fragile encoding makes that recovery path data-dependent on otherwise valid identifiers."},{"body":"`FsTaskRunLineageStore::append_task_run` still writes whatever `TaskRunEntry` it is handed (`src/adapters/fs.rs:2682-2691`). Because `milestone_id` remains optional and `read_task_runs_from_path` only backfills it in memory after deserialization (`src/adapters/fs.rs:2525-2533`), any direct caller of the public append API can still create brand-new NDJSON rows with no explicit `milestone_id`. That violates the new self-contained-entry invariant introduced by this task and leaves on-disk lineage incomplete until some later rewrite happens to touch the row.","rationale":"The task’s contract was to make lineage entries self-contained. Leaving one public write path unconstrained means the adapter does not actually enforce that persistence invariant."}],"summary":"Reviewed the milestone-lineage change set in `model.rs`, `service.rs`, and `fs.rs`, and ran `cargo test milestone_record -- --nocapture` successfully. I found 2 remaining correctness gaps."}